Understanding Network Commands in Linux

In this section, we will learn how to identify the IP address of a system and understand basic network-related commands. These commands are very important when working with servers, especially in DevOps and cloud environments.


1. hostname -i

Command:
hostname -i

Example Output:
172.31.79.254

Explanation:

This command is used to display the IP address of the current system.

Every system has a hostname, and this command returns the IP address mapped to that hostname.

In simple terms, it tells you:
“What is the IP address of this machine?”


2. ip addr

Command:
ip addr

Explanation:

This command displays complete information about all network interfaces available in the system.

You will see multiple sections in the output. The most important ones are explained below.

Loopback Interface (lo)

This is a special interface used for internal communication within the system.

Example:
inet 127.0.0.1/8

This IP address always refers to the same machine. It is mainly used for testing and internal processes.

Every Linux system will have this interface.

Main Network Interface (ens5)

This is the actual network interface used for communication with other systems.

Example:
inet 172.31.79.254/20

Breakdown of this line:

inet → Indicates IPv4 address
172.31.79.254 → IP address of the system
/20 → Subnet mask

This is usually a private IP address when working in cloud platforms like AWS.

Additional Details:

state UP → The network interface is active
dynamic → IP address is assigned automatically using DHCP
mtu 9001 → Maximum packet size


3. ip route

Command:
ip route

Explanation:

This command shows how the system sends data to other networks.

It defines the path that packets take to reach their destination.

Default Route

Example:
default via 172.31.64.1 dev ens5

Explanation:

default → Used when the destination is outside the current network
via 172.31.64.1 → The gateway through which traffic is sent
dev ens5 → The network interface used

This means that if the system does not know how to reach a destination, it will send the request to the gateway.

Network Route

Example:
172.31.64.0/20 dev ens5

This represents the local network range.

Any system within this range can be accessed directly without using a gateway.

Source IP

Example:
src 172.31.79.254

This is the IP address used by your system while sending requests.


Simple Understanding

You can think of networking like this:

Your IP address is like your house address.
The gateway is like the main road.
Routing defines how you travel from one place to another.

If the destination is within your local area, you can go directly.
If the destination is outside your area, you must use the main road (gateway).


Additional Useful Date Commands

Command:
date

Displays current date and time.

Command:
date +"%d"

Displays day of the month.

Command:
date +"%m"

Displays month.

Command:
date +"%y"

Displays last two digits of the year.

Command:
date +"%Y"

Displays full year.

Command:
date +"%H"

Displays hour (24-hour format).

Command:
date +"%M"

Displays minutes.

Command:
date +"%S"

Displays seconds.

Command:
date +"%A"

Displays full day name.

Command:
date +"%B"

Displays full month name.

Command:
date +"%D"

Displays date in MM/DD/YY format.

Command:
date +"%F"

Displays date in YYYY-MM-DD format.

Command:
date +"%T"

Displays time in HH:MM:SS format.

Command:
date -u

Displays date and time in UTC.

Interview Preparation

If asked how to check IP address in Linux:

Use:
hostname -i
ip addr

If asked how to check routing:

Use:
ip route


Conclusion

These commands are essential for understanding system networking.

They help in identifying IP addresses, analyzing network interfaces, and understanding how data flows between systems.

This knowledge is very important when working with servers, cloud platforms, and DevOps tools.
